Migration is a grueling endurance test, but one male humpback whale set a record-breaking journey for love. Traveling across three oceans, the whale migrated from the eastern Pacific to the Indian Ocean, ultimately reaching Zanzibar’s coast. This epic voyage represents the longest great-circle distance ever documented for a humpback whale, connecting breeding grounds in the eastern Pacific and southwest Indian Ocean. Scientists believe the whale undertook the journey to increase its chances of finding a mate, likely navigating ocean currents and interacting with other humpback groups along the way. Ted Cheeseman, study co-author from Southern Cross University, called the discovery “exciting,” noting their initial reaction was disbelief at such an extraordinary feat.
